<h1>Homework of the Statistics session</h1>
<ul>
<li><ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Use Simulations to deduce the distribution of the summation of three standard normal distributions. Guess what is the class of this distribution?</li>
</ol></li>
<li><ol start="2" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Use Simulations to deduce the distribution of the average of three Poisson distributions, and the average of 5000 Poisson distributions. Compare and describe the differences.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><ol start="3" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Explain what is a confidence interval. Use simulations to demonstrate the characteristics of confidence interval.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><ol start="4" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Simulate two groups of data (1000 observations for each group). These data are binary (1 or 0). Group I has 30% of 0s while Group II 70%. Choose an appropriate testing procedure to compare the difference.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><ol start="5" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Suppose you need to calculate the standard deviation of a string of data that appears one by one. You can only record one number representing the history of previous data. What should you do?</li>
</ol></li>
</ul>

<div id="assignment-1" class="slide section level2 bigger">
<h1>Assignment 1</h1>
<ul>
<li>Use Simulations to deduce the distribution of the summation of three standard normal distributions. Guess what is the class of this distribution?</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># assume independent identical distributed (i.i.d).</span>

<span class="co"># generate data from three iid standard normal distributions</span>
a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dt">n =</span> <span class="dv">10000</span>, <span class="dt">mean =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dt">sd =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>)
b &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dt">n =</span> <span class="dv">10000</span>, <span class="dt">mean =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dt">sd =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>)
c &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dt">n =</span> <span class="dv">10000</span>, <span class="dt">mean =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dt">sd =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>)

<span class="co"># calculate the sum of three distributions</span>
d &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a +<span class="st"> </span>b +<span class="st"> </span>c
<span class="kw">mean</span>(d)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 0.02194033</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">sd</span>(d)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 1.737068</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">hist</span>(d, <span class="dt">breaks =</span> <span class="dv">100</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># generate a set of data from normal distribution with mean = 1 and variance = 3</span>
e &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dt">n =</span> <span class="dv">10000</span>, <span class="dt">mean =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dt">sd =</span><span class="kw">sqrt</span>(<span class="dv">3</span>))
<span class="kw">hist</span>(e, <span class="dt">breaks =</span> <span class="dv">100</span>, <span class="dt">xlim =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(-<span class="dv">6</span>,<span class="dv">6</span>))</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># use Shapiro test to test for normality</span>
<span class="kw">shapiro.test</span>(d[<span class="dv">1</span>:<span class="dv">5000</span>])</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  d[1:5000]
## W = 0.99956, p-value = 0.3292</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="assignment-2" class="slide section level2 bigger">
<h1>Assignment 2</h1>
<ul>
<li>Use Simulations to deduce the distribution of the average of three Poisson distributions, and the average of 5000 Poisson distributions. Compare and describe the differences.</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># Generate 3 Poisson distributions</span>
a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rpois</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>)
b &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rpois</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>)
c &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rpois</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>)

<span class="co"># calculate the averge of these three Poission distributions</span>
d &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>(a +<span class="st"> </span>b +<span class="st"> </span>c)/<span class="dv">3</span>

<span class="co"># plot d</span>
<span class="kw">hist</span>(d, <span class="dt">breaks =</span> <span class="dv">100</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">mean</span>(d)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 3.061</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">sd</span>(d)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 0.9967978</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># use Shapiro test to test for normality</span>
<span class="kw">shapiro.test</span>(d)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  d
## W = 0.98204, p-value = 9.22e-10</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># Generate 5000 Poisson distributions, I used a small trick here to simplify simulation</span>
e &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rpois</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>*<span class="dv">5000</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>)
e &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">matrix</span>(e, <span class="dv">5000</span>, <span class="dv">1000</span>)
f &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">apply</span>(e,<span class="dv">1</span>,mean)

<span class="co"># plot f</span>
<span class="kw">hist</span>(f, <span class="dt">breaks =</span> <span class="dv">100</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># use Shapiro test to test for normality</span>
<span class="kw">shapiro.test</span>(f)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  f
## W = 0.99976, p-value = 0.8641</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="assignment-3" class="slide section level2 bigger">
<h1>Assignment 3</h1>
<ul>
<li>Explain what is a confidence interval. Use simulations to demonstrate the characteristics of confidence interval.</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># Generate one set of 1000 observations from a standard normal distribution</span>
a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)

<span class="co"># calculate the lower bound and upper bound of 95% confidence interval</span>
LB &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">mean</span>(a) -<span class="st"> </span><span class="fl">1.96</span>*<span class="kw">sd</span>(a)/<span class="kw">sqrt</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>)
UB &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">mean</span>(a) +<span class="st"> </span><span class="fl">1.96</span>*<span class="kw">sd</span>(a)/<span class="kw">sqrt</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>)

LB</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] -0.04428136</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">UB</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 0.07871558</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># Simulate 1000 rounds</span>
LB &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>()
UB &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>()

for(i in <span class="dv">1</span>:<span class="dv">1000</span>)
{
  a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)
  LB[i] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">mean</span>(a) -<span class="st"> </span><span class="fl">1.96</span>*<span class="kw">sd</span>(a)/<span class="kw">sqrt</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>)
  UB[i] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">mean</span>(a) +<span class="st"> </span><span class="fl">1.96</span>*<span class="kw">sd</span>(a)/<span class="kw">sqrt</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>)
}

<span class="co"># constract a data.frame with each row as a confidence interval from one round of simulation</span>
CI &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(<span class="dt">LB =</span> LB, <span class="dt">UB =</span> UB)
<span class="kw">head</span>(CI)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##            LB         UB
## 1 -0.04250195 0.08255430
## 2 -0.07709171 0.04453959
## 3 -0.06102636 0.05815227
## 4 -0.07177297 0.05723454
## 5 -0.04792604 0.07743875
## 6 -0.09660040 0.02815941</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="co"># The number of times that a confidence interval doesn't contain the true value</span>
<span class="kw">nrow</span>(CI[(LB -<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">0</span>)*(UB -<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">0</span>) &gt;<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">0</span>,])</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 45</code></pre>

<div id="assignment-5" class="slide section level2 bigger">
<h1>Assignment 5</h1>
<ul>
<li>Suppose you need to calculate the standard deviation of a string of data that appears one by one. You can only record one number representing the history of previous data. What should you do?</li>
</ul>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
 \sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i-\overline{x})^2 &amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i^2 - 2x_i \overline{x} + {\overline{x}}^2) \\
&amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i^2)-\sum_{i=1}^{n}2x_i\overline{x}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}{\overline{x}}^2 \\
&amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i^2)-2\overline{x}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_i+n{\overline{x}}^2 \\
&amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i^2)-2\overline{x}n\overline{x}+n{\overline{x}}^2 \\
&amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i^2)-n{\overline{x}}^2 \\
&amp;= \sum_{i=1}^{n-1}(x_i^2) + {x_n}^2-n{((\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}x_i + x_n)/n)}^2
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
